00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:54.970
So as Mario mentioned,
my expertise

00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:59.110
is in the topic of the human
brain's attention system.

00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:04.300
And the bulk of my research
over many years of my lab

00:03:04.300 --> 00:03:07.540
has been on understanding the
brain mechanisms of attention.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:10.390
So we use a variety of cognitive
neuroscience techniques

00:03:10.390 --> 00:03:12.400
to study attention.

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:15.700
Things like functional
MRI, brain wave recordings,

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:18.130
or Event-Related
Potentials, ERPs,

00:03:18.130 --> 00:03:21.660
as well as behavioral tasks that
are sort of like simple video

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:24.760
games that allow us to tax
attention in specific ways

00:03:24.760 --> 00:03:27.520
that we can measure the impact.

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:29.942
And through doing this,
we've learned a lot about how

00:03:29.942 --> 00:03:31.150
attention works in the brain.

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:33.190
And we basically have
learned that where

00:03:33.190 --> 00:03:36.130
we direct our attention
biases the processing

00:03:36.130 --> 00:03:37.799
of the rest of the brain.

00:03:37.799 --> 00:03:40.090
And in some ways, you can
think about this as attention

00:03:40.090 --> 00:03:42.250
being the brain's boss.

00:03:42.250 --> 00:03:45.460
Wherever attention goes, the
rest of the brain will follow.

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:48.070
Which means it has a powerful
responsibility with regard

00:03:48.070 --> 00:03:50.495
to where we put our attention.

00:03:50.495 --> 00:03:52.120
And through the course
of understanding

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:54.160
the basics of
attention, we've also

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:56.740
come to understand that
there are some things that

00:03:56.740 --> 00:04:00.070
are essentially like
kryptonite for our brain's

00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:00.970
system of attention.

00:04:00.970 --> 00:04:02.420
And those are listed here.

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:06.940
We know that with high
stress, poor mood, and threat,

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:10.270
our attention system will
become compromised and degraded.

00:04:10.270 --> 00:04:12.531
It won't function the
way we want it to,

00:04:12.531 --> 00:04:14.530
which is particularly
problematic because that's

00:04:14.530 --> 00:04:18.100
probably-- those are the kinds
of circumstances in which we

00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:20.980
want to be absolutely sure that
our attention is working well

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:22.510
because we'll lean on it.

00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:25.670
And after understanding
this for several years,

00:04:25.670 --> 00:04:28.150
it became sort of a
compelling question for me

00:04:28.150 --> 00:04:30.110
to figure out what
we could do about it.

00:04:30.110 --> 00:04:32.110
So if we know there
are circumstances

00:04:32.110 --> 00:04:34.070
in which attention
is compromised,

00:04:34.070 --> 00:04:36.790
how might we train the
brain's attention system

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:38.860
to be protected against this?

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:41.530
Because it's unlikely for
the kinds of professions

00:04:41.530 --> 00:04:44.560
and personnel that we
involve in our research,

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:47.440
it's unlikely that we can
avoid them ever having--

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:49.120
in fact, as human
beings, it's unlikely

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:51.190
that we can avoid
having experiences

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:53.140
in our lives of stress,
poor mood, and threat.

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:55.150
I wish we could, but sorry.

00:04:55.150 --> 00:04:56.650
So that's where
mindfulness training

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:58.570
